    <section>
      <title>Nuclear Security Summit</title>
      <abstract>Fallout from the Nuclear Security Summit involves over 50 countries.</abstract>
      <chapter>
        <title>China and Russia</title>
        <paragraph>The Nuclear Security Summit that just ended Friday in Washington, D.C. wrangled over several thorny nuclear proliferation and terrorism issues.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>But the two countries on everyone’s mind were China and Russia. </paragraph>
        <paragraph>China, because they have started on the world’s largest nuclear build-up in 50 years.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>And Russia, because they decided not to attend at all.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>Russia has the most nuclear weapons and nuclear materials in the world and they are a key player in the success of the Iran nuclear deal.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>But Russia’s economy continues to deteriorate, leading to crumbling nuclear infrastructure and a lack of funding for nuclear scientists and inspectors.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>there is no doubt that China is committed to help thwart nuclear terrorism and rogue states, and is serious about nuclear safety and security.</paragraph>

        <paragraph>Summit goals:</paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Reduction of Global Nuclear weapons.</item>
            <item>Reduction of Nuclear Materials Stocks.</item>
            <item>Increase of security Against The Nuclear plants.</item>
            <item>Protection of radioactive sources used in the Civil Sector.</item>
            <item>Fight against international smuggling of nuclear material.</item>
          </list>
       </paragraph>

